synchronous and asynchronous how to achieve
Synchronous

Tasks execute one after another
Each task waits for the previous one to finish
👉 Blocking behavior

Asynchronous

Tasks execute independently
No need to wait for previous task
👉 Non-blocking behavior

How to achieve in Java
1. Synchronous (default behavior)
Normal method calls
Single-thread execution
void process() {
    step1();
    step2(); // waits
}
2. Asynchronous ways
a) Using Thread
new Thread(() -> {
    System.out.println("Async task");
}).start();
b) Using ExecutorService (recommended)
ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(2);

executor.submit(() -> {
    System.out.println("Async task");
});

executor.shutdown();

“Synchronous execution is blocking and runs tasks sequentially, while asynchronous execution is non-blocking and can be achieved in Java using Threads, 
ExecutorService, or CompletableFuture.”
