Static synchronous and asynchronous difference 
Types of synchronisation
1) Method-Level Synchronization
Entire method is locked
Only one thread can execute the method at a time
synchronized void print() {
    // critical section
}

👉 Lock is on the object (this)

2. Block-Level Synchronization
Only a specific block is locked (better performance)
void print() {
    synchronized(this) {
        // critical section
    }
}

👉 More efficient than method-level

3. Static Synchronization
Used for static methods
Lock is on the Class object
synchronized static void display() {
    // critical section
}

👉 Lock = ClassName.class

4. Class-Level Synchronization (Explicit)
Manually lock on class object
void show() {
    synchronized(ClassName.class) {
        // critical section
    }
}
“Synchronization in Java can be method-level, block-level, static, and class-level, depending on whether the lock is applied on an object or the class.”
